class Solution {
public:
    int numberOfStableArrays(int zero, int one, int limit) {
        int MOD = 1e9 + 7;
        long long res = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i <= limit; i++) {
            res = res * (i - zero) * (i - one) % MOD;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(limit)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: We use dynamic programming to solve this problem. We iterate from 1 to limit and for each i, we calculate the number of ways to fill the first i elements of the array such that the number of 0s is exactly zero and the number of 1s is exactly one. We use the fact that the number of ways to fill the first i elements is the product of the number of ways to fill the first i-1 elements and the number of ways to fill the first i-1 elements with a 0 or a 1.

